shows that English associations once were widespread, taking hold in colonial America, spreading to Canada and then encompassing all of the empire. Celebrating saints days, expressing pride in the monarch and national heroes, providing charity to the national poor, and forging mutual aid societies mutual, were all features of English life overseas. In fact, the English simply resembled other immigrant groups too much to be dismissed as the unproblematic, invisible immigrants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBritish AmericansxHistory. 0aEnglishzNorth AmericaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAssociational Culture.  aBritish.  aCanada.  aDiaspora.  aEmigration.  aEnglish.  aEthnicity.  aImmigration.  aUnited States.1 aBueltmann, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacRaild, Donald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacRaild, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610372740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526103727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526103727/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles